Data Types in Java
   In Java, a data type tells the computer what kind of data a variable can store.
   Example: int age = 20;

Two Main Types of Data Types in Java
1.Primitive Data Types
   Primitive data types store simple values.
   java has 8 primitive types:

Data Type     	Description           Example
byte        Small whole number	      byte b = 10;
short	      Medium whole number	      short s = 100;
int	        Whole number	            int num = 500;
long	      Large whole number        long big = 100000L;
float      	Decimal number            float f = 5.5f; 
            (less precision)	       
double	     Decimal number           double d = 10.99; 
            (more precision)	       


2.Non-Primitive (Reference) Data Types
     Non-primitive types store references (addresses) to objects.
     Examples:
     1 String 
     2 Arrays
     3 Classes
     4 Interfaces

Example:

String name = "John";
int[] numbers = {1, 2, 3};
 Difference Between Primitive and Non-Primitive
    Primitive	            Non-Primitive
Stores actual value	    Stores reference (address)
Fixed size	            Size depends on object
Cannot call methods	    Can call methods
Example: int, double   	Example: String, Array

Example Program
class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int age = 25;           // Primitive
        double salary = 5000.5; // Primitive
        String name = "Alice";  // Non-Primitive
        
        System.out.println(name + " is " + age + " years old.");
    }
}

